  Name: Guzeppi
  Icon: {fileID: -1465489678553493566, guid: bdf9b2df1b7e9ab48b44781ca0257510, type: 3}
  HasInteraction: 0
  interactionType: 2
  Greeting: Guzeppi the Smugler
  Day1Dialog:
  - "Welcome to the ramparts, boy. See the walls? They were built strong \u2014 Spanish
    engineer Pietro Pardo designed them to resist the sea, but the Turks hammer from
    land.\nWe patch breaches, rebuild sections with stone, and reinforce the points.\nThey
    cannot tunnel here \u2014 the rock is too hard. But each shell weakens our walls."
  Day2FirstTimeDialog:
  - 'The ravelin fell yesterday, boy. Outer works smashed.

    We shored up the
    demi-bastions, tightened the parapets.

    Every breach we fix, the enemy hammers
    again. Still, the fort must stand.'
  Day2MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Yesterday we rebuilt the ravelin walls \u2014 today, fresh stones are shattered
    again.\nI work with masons and volunteers, reinforcing the weak points.\nThe
    Turks swarm, yet our walls hold\u2026 just barely."
  Day3FirstTimeDialog:
  - "Dragut has arrived, boy. His guns pound from Gallows\u2019 Point and the land
    front.\nWe rebuild faster than they can break, stacking rubble and stone, sealing
    holes with earth.\nEach night, reinforcements from Vittoriosa bring more help
    \u2014 without them, the fort would fall."
  Day3MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Yesterday I patched the demi-bastion; today, it is shattered again.\nDragut\u2019s
    orders doubled the fire. Each shell cracks stone and morale alike.\nStill, we
    strengthen the bastions, fill ditches, and prepare for the next assault."
  Day4FirstTimeDialog:
  - 'Another assault failed. The walls bleed stone and mortar, but stand.

    We
    reinforce every night, work in darkness, while others fire from the ramparts.

    If
    we fall, all Malta falls. Every stone matters.'
  Day4MetBeforeDialog:
  - "The Turks charge again, boy. Breaches appear, but we fill them, build scaffolds,
    hammer and shove stone into place.\nI pray each wall holds, each bastion survives
    another volley.\nThis is more than engineering \u2014 it is survival."
  Day5FirstTimeDialog:
  - "Tomorrow may see the bloodiest day yet. Many men have already died. Every life
    here is fragile, and the fort\u2019s defenders cling desperately to hope."
  Day5MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Final day, boy. Every patient, every wound, every life depends on what we\u2019ve
    done. Remember the faces here; they are the price of holding St. Elmo against
    overwhelming odds."
  dayNumber: 1
  metOnday1: 0
  metOnday2: 0
  metOnday3: 0
  metOnday4: 0
  metOnday5: 0
